node-idempotent-error-safe-disposers:
Consider the following two cases:

```
{
  using foo = new MyDisposable();
}

{
  using foo = new MyDisposable();
  throw new Error('boom');
}
```

The disposer in each case is going to be called. Unfortunately, however, the disposer has no idea if there is an exception pending or not. Let's say our `MyDisposable` has two possible modes: one is a clean, graceful async shutdown, the second is a dirty, abrupt shutdown in case of an error. Since the disposer does not know whether it is being called with a pending exception or not we cannot safely assume within the disposer that a graceful async shutdown should be used. Instead, we have to assume it is an exception case.

```js
class MyDisposer {
  #closed = false;
  #aborted = false;

  close() {
    if (this.#closed) return;
    this.#closed = true;
  }

  abort() {
    this.#aborted = true;
    this.close();
  }

  [Symbol.dispose]() {
    this.abort();
  }
}
```

