Looking at the `build_mamba_layer()` function, it appears complex, but actually it boils down to something like this:

```c++
build_mamba_layer(inp) {
    rec_state = static_cast<...>(mstate);

    conv = rec_state->update_conv(inp); // analogous to unified get_k() + cpy_k()
    ssm  = rec_state->update_ssm (inp); // analogous to unified get_v() + cpy_v()

    common = get_common(model);

    do_something_with_conv(model, common, conv);
    do_something_with_ssm (model, common, ssm);
}
```

The `get_common(model)` and `do_something_with_...(model, ...)` parts have to be extracted out of this function and remain implemented in `llama-model.cpp` because they use model tensors and do not depend on the memory module. The `update_conv()` and `update_ssm()` function have to be implemented only once in the `class llama_kv_cache_recurrent`. Internally, they can use a helper `build_recurrent_state()` function to deduplicate the code. Note that the hybrid cache will call these methods from the recurrent cache instance and won't have to implement them a second time.

When you decompose the function like this, the implementation becomes much simpler:

```c++
build_mamba_layer(inp) {
    rec_state = static_cast<...based_on_inp...>(m_state);

    conv = rec_state->update_conv(inp);
    ssm  = rec_state->update_ssm (inp);

    return { conv, ssm };
}
```

This is much easier to overload multiple times for different `inp` types. I would even split it one more time:

```c++
// llama-graph:

// one for recurrent and one for hybrid
build_mamba_conv(inp) {
    rec_state = static_cast<...based on inp...>(m_state);

    conv = rec_state->update_conv(inp->get_s_copy());
    
    return conv;
}

// one for recurrent and one for hybrid
build_mamba_ssm(inp) {
    rec_state = static_cast<...based on inp...>(m_state);

    ssm = rec_state->update_ssm(inp->get_s_copy());
    
    return ssm;
}
```

I hope I'm not missing something, but I think this should work and should be clean.

